#860
@@dThe Void Catacombs Lower Archive@@n~
A collection of records maintained beneath the catacomb complex,


accessible from the undercroft. The archive tracks the full history


of Kel'Shadra from the perspective of those who served it: how the


entity was discovered, the initial compact with the sorcerers,


the gradual corruption of the original guardians, and the centuries


of undead service that followed.


~
8201 11
D0
~
~
0 -1 715
E
records history catacombs compact~
The history from the servants' perspective is surprisingly honest about


their mistakes. The original guardians knew they were being changed by


the void energy. They accepted it because the alternative was death.


Their acceptance is documented with extraordinary clarity by the people


who made it - a record of how good people become something else, one


compromise at a time.


~
S
#900
@@bThe Void-Gate Chamber@@n~
A chamber accessible only to those who have completed all of the


citadel's major challenges: the catacombs, the spire, the eternal


corridors, the binding circle. A void-gate occupies the center of


the room - a circular portal showing a space beyond the material plane.


It is not active, but it could be activated. Whether it leads somewhere


useful or somewhere terrible is the question.


~
8201 11
D2
~
~
0 -1 678
E
void-gate portal inactive~
The void-gate bears the seals of the original sorcerers who created


Kel'Shadra's binding. The gate was their emergency exit - a way out


of the plane entirely if the entity broke free. They never used it.


The seals are intact. The gate is functional. Where it leads, no one


currently alive can say.


~
S
#901
@@bThe Chamber of First Contact@@n~
A historical chamber that is both museum and memorial. The exact spot


where the sorcerers first made contact with Kel'Shadra is preserved


here, marked by a circle of void-glass that formed when the entity


first manifested. The glass records the event perfectly, showing it


from multiple angles as if filmed: the contact, the compact, and the


first signs of what was really happening.


~
8201 11
D0
~
~
0 -1 900
E
glass recording contact compact~
Watching the glass's recording: the sorcerers were brilliant, confident,


and completely wrong about what they were dealing with. Kel'Shadra


agreed to their terms easily because the terms were trivial constraints


on an entity of its power. The compact gave it exactly what it wanted:


a way to remain in the material plane. The sorcerers celebrated while


the entity waited.


~
S
#902
@@bThe Observation Gallery@@n~
A gallery overlooking the void-gate chamber from above. Arrow slits


allowed the original sorcerers to observe the gate without being in


the room. From here, the full apparatus of the gate is visible, along


with the mechanisms used to control it. Several of those mechanisms


are broken. Several appear to have been deliberately sabotaged.


~
8201 11
D2
~
~
0 -1 901
E
mechanisms broken sabotaged~
The sabotage is systematic and knowledgeable - someone who understood


the gate's mechanisms destroyed the pieces that would allow the gate


to be opened remotely or against its users' will. This was done to


prevent the gate from being used as a weapon against the people


standing within it. Someone sacrificed the gate's remote operation


to protect future users.


~
S
#950
@@bThe Aftermath Chamber@@n~
A room accessible only after defeating Kel'Shadra's physical manifestation


in the Void Sanctum. With the entity's focus broken, certain areas of


the citadel have changed: this chamber, formerly inaccessible, has opened.


It contains the physical remains of the original sorcerers - not dead,


exactly, but suspended in the moment of their ultimate failure.


~
8201 11
D0
~
~
0 -1 695
E
sorcerers suspended failure aftermath~
The original sorcerers who summoned Kel'Shadra and failed to control


it have existed in this suspended state for three centuries, held


by the entity as both trophy and source of continued power. With the


entity weakened or destroyed, their state has become something new:


not death, not life, not quite peace, but something like release.


They do not speak, but the expressions on their preserved faces change


as you enter: from the frozen rictus of horror to something approaching


relief.


~
S
#951
@@bThe Resolution Hall@@n~
The final room of the citadel - the one that only exists after the


entity's defeat. The hall is simply an exit: a passage that leads


through the citadel's walls to the outside world. The walls here


are bare, the architecture plain. No void-stone, no dark enchantments,


no screaming faces on the sconces. Just a way out, open at last.


~
8201 11
D0
~
~
0 -1 950
E
exit outside passage out~
The passage is short and ends in an ordinary door of weathered wood


with an iron handle. Beyond it, cold air and daylight. After everything


the citadel contains, the exit is deliberately unremarkable: a reminder


that the world outside, with all its ordinariness, is the point. What


was done here was done so that ordinary doors could remain possible.


~
S
